        "title": "Answer",
        "style": null,
        "decorator": null,
        "content": "<h3>Dead stock is essentially a stock of products that are not likely to ever leave the shelves. Products might be selling well, but with every change of seasonal collections, with every inventory re-stock there&#39;s an ever growing pile of products that just don&#39;t sell and the additional weight they add to your business is dragging it down. That is referred to as dead stock (or deadstock/headstock).</h3>\n\n<p>A common mistake made by retail businesses is not getting rid of their dead stock, meaning these products continue to occupy space in the warehouse and slowly drain valuable finances which could be allocated towards business&#39; growth.</p>\n\n<p>What does headstock mean for your business? To get a better idea, try calculating carrying costs you have by holding on to the items that define deadstock. Look at your storage costs - the rental costs for warehouses, the money spent on utilities, insurance, security, and equipment, etc. All these costs would need to be offset by the revenue from product sales, however as deadstock items are not making any sales, they keep adding to costs instead of helping to cover them.</p>\n\n<p>Another important topic here is missed opportunities, because headstock is essentially shelf space that is lost that could be holding more of your top selling products.</p>\n\n<p>The correct approach to dead inventory management is critical &ndash; and can really increase your ROI.</p>\n",
